# Mortar Follow-Up Plan

## Goal

Break the mortar polish/gameplay request into small, independently reviewable changes.

Requested changes:
- Mortar impacts should deal friendly fire at the normal damage rate.
- Mortars should render a visible black shell projectile fired from the mortar.
- The shell should read like an overhead arc: compressed near launch, stretched near midpoint,
  compressed again before impact.
- Autocast mortars should avoid firing at target points where friendly units or buildings would be
  damaged, assuming friendly units hold their current positions.
- Dust cloud animation should be doubled in size, thicker, and last twice as long.
- Mortar wheels should be slightly thinner, less circular, and more pill shaped.
- Attack preview red dotted lines and crosshair should use a darker hue.
- Mortar attack previews should remain visible until the mortar round hits.
- Multi-selected mortars should support holding `X` / fire hotkey and clicking repeatedly to fire
  multiple mortars without the second click deselecting the group.
- Scout cars should get the same repeated hotkey-click behavior.
- Reflect the final behavior in the relevant design docs.

## Phase 1 - Friendly Fire And Autocast Safety

Server behavior:
- Change mortar AOE resolution so friendly units and buildings take the same impact damage as enemy
  entities when inside the mortar impact radius.
- Keep fog/event projection safe: friendly fire must not reveal hidden enemy positions to players
  who could not otherwise see them.
- Update autocast target selection so a mortar rejects an attack point if any owned unit or owned
  building would be inside the damaging impact area, using current positions only.
- Keep manual fire dangerous: player-commanded mortar fire should still be allowed onto friendly
  units/buildings.

Tests:
- Mortar impact damages friendly units at the same rate as enemies.
- Mortar impact damages friendly buildings when inside radius.
- Autocast refuses or skips a shot that would hit owned units/buildings.
- Autocast still fires at valid targets when no owned entity would be hit.
- Manual fire can still be ordered onto a point that contains owned entities.

Patch notes:
- Mortar shells now cause full friendly fire.
- Autocast mortars avoid shots that would hit your own current unit/building positions.

## Phase 2 - Projectile And Impact Preview Lifetime

Protocol/client behavior:
- Represent mortar launch-to-impact timing on the client well enough to draw a projectile and keep
  the warning preview alive until impact.
- Prefer using existing mortar target/impact events if they already carry enough timing and
  position data. If not, add the smallest protocol extension needed and mirror it in
  `server/src/protocol.rs`, `client/src/protocol.js`, and `docs/design/protocol.md`.
- Render a black mortar shell traveling from the firing mortar toward the impact point.
- Animate shell shape over flight progress:
  - launch: slightly compressed, suggesting it is pointing upward;
  - midpoint: slightly stretched;
  - pre-impact: compressed again before disappearing into the impact.
- Keep the red dotted attack line/crosshair visible until the associated mortar round hits.
- Use a darker red hue for the dotted line and crosshair.

Tests/checks:
- Manual mortar fire shows a projectile from launcher to target.
- Autocast mortar fire shows the same projectile for the firing player.
- The preview disappears when the round impacts, not earlier.
- Hidden enemy mortar fire still does not leak forbidden positions.

Patch notes:
- Mortar fire now has a visible shell and longer warning marker so players can dodge, including
  around their own autocast shots.

## Phase 3 - Dust Cloud And Mortar Art Polish

Client rendering:
- Double the mortar impact dust cloud size.
- Make the dust thicker/more opaque or denser.
- Make the dust animation last twice as long.
- Adjust mortar wheels to be slightly thinner.
- Make wheels less circular and more pill shaped.

Checks:
- Mortar impacts remain readable at normal zoom.
- Larger/longer dust does not obscure too much battlefield state.
- Mortar art remains visually distinct from AT guns and machine gunners.

Patch notes:
- Mortar impacts have larger, thicker, longer-lasting dust clouds.
- Mortar wheels have a slimmer pill-shaped profile.

## Phase 4 - Repeated Hotkey Targeting For Mortars And Scout Cars

Client input behavior:
- When multiple mortars are selected and the player holds `X` or the fire hotkey, repeated clicks
  should issue repeated fire commands instead of treating the second click as a normal selection
  click.
- Preserve selection while the hotkey-targeting mode is active.
- Each click should pick an eligible selected mortar, so multiple mortars can be assigned across
  multiple clicks.
- Apply the same repeated hotkey-click behavior to scout cars for their relevant command.
- Keep existing normal click selection behavior when no command hotkey is held.

Tests/checks:
- Multi-select mortars, hold `X`, click several target points: selection remains intact and
  multiple mortar commands are issued.
- Multi-select scout cars, hold the relevant hotkey, click several target points: selection remains
  intact and multiple commands are issued.
- Releasing the hotkey returns clicks to normal selection/command behavior.

Patch notes:
- Holding the fire hotkey now supports repeated point targeting for selected Mortars and Scout
  Cars without losing selection.

## Phase 5 - Design Documentation

Update docs after behavior is implemented:
- `docs/design/server-sim.md`: mortar friendly-fire behavior, autocast safety assumptions, and any
  command/autocast rules that belong in the sim contract.
- `docs/design/client-ui.md`: shell projectile, longer warning preview, darker preview color,
  dust cloud animation, wheel art adjustment, and repeated hotkey targeting behavior.
- `docs/design/protocol.md`: only if mortar launch/preview/projectile data requires a wire change.
- Refresh relevant `docs/context/*.md` section pointers only if design document structure shifts.

## Suggested Implementation Order

1. Friendly fire and autocast safety.
2. Projectile/preview lifetime, including protocol only if required.
3. Dust and mortar art polish.
4. Repeated hotkey targeting for mortars and scout cars.
5. Design docs and final verification.

